Solution: To find \(P(A)\) given \(P(A \cup B) = 0.76\) and \(P(A \cup B') = 0.87\), use the formula for the union of two sets and the fact that the sample space has probability 1.

The events \(A \cup B\) and \(A \cup B'\) cover the entire sample space because their union is \(A \cup B \cup B' = A \cup S = S\), where \(S\) is the sample space. Their intersection is \(A\), since \((A \cup B) \cap (A \cup B') = A \cup (B \cap B') = A \cup \emptyset = A\).

Using the inclusion-exclusion principle for the two sets \(X = A \cup B\) and \(Y = A \cup B'\):

\[
P(X \cup Y) = P(X) + P(Y) - P(X \cap Y)
\]

